title: My Brother-in-Law Vilified Us Online. Should We Still Have Him Over?
content: A reader asks whether a defamatory post on social media is cause for disinviting a dinner guest.

title: ‘The Most Beautiful Boy in the World’ Review: A Cautionary Tale
content: The 1971 film “Death in Venice” showcased the delicate androgyny of Bjorn Andresen’s face and form, but the changes it wrought on his life are indelible.

title: In the Los Angeles Suburbs, They Stretched Their Budget to Buy a Family Home. Which Would You Choose?
content: In pursuit of a four-bedroom house within reasonable commuting distance of downtown, a couple toured nearly 40 homes to get the right mix of space and amenities. Here’s what they found.

title: ‘Our Differences in Age and Skin Color Meant Nothing to Us.’
content: Constance Collins and Matthew Steuer, 24 years her senior, met five years ago as each was about to begin a teaching job in Africa.

title: Making Streetside Dining Permanent
content: New York is moving to make outdoor restaurant sheds permanent, but some activists are fiercely opposed.

title: Moderna vs. Pfizer: Both Knockouts, but One Seems to Have the Edge
content: A series of studies found that the Moderna vaccine seemed to be more protective as the months passed than the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine. Here’s why.

title: Willie Garson, ‘Sex and the City’ Actor, Dies at 57
content: Mr. Garson was also known for his role as the con man Mozzie on “White Collar.”

title: The UnTrump Presidency Slams Into Trumpness
content: Angry allies. Border bedlam. Sound familiar?

title: A Governor’s High School Basketball Dreams Are Blocked. And He Is Crying Foul.
content: As his state was battered by Covid-19, Gov. Jim Justice of West Virginia applied to coach a boys’ team in his spare time. When the school board rejected him, he threatened to haul the members before a judge.
